explanation: For MISRA C rule checking about pointer const-qualification we must confirm the types and constness of all identifiers used in the function: 1) force_md5, force_sha256, force_sha512_256 — their declarations (type, pointer vs non‑pointer, const/volatile qualifiers). If any of these are pointers, MISRA requires checking whether they should point to const; if they are plain scalars there is no pointer concern. 2) enum MHD_DigestAuthMultiAlgo3 — the full type/definition to ensure the function returns an enum (value) rather than a pointer type or typedef to a pointer. 3) MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_MULT_ALGO3_MD5, MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_MULT_ALGO3_SHA256, MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_MULT_ALGO3_SHA512_256, MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_MULT_ALGO3_ANY_NON_SESSION — the enum/constant definitions to confirm they are enum constants (not pointer macros) and to ensure no hidden pointer usage. These symbols collectively allow determination whether the function uses or returns any pointer that should be const-qualified per MISRA; if all are non‑pointer scalars/enums, the rule is not violated.
